# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: biomaterials
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Prior to 1925, the materials used in implant surgery were primarily relatively pure metals.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] The success of these materials was surprising considering the relatively primitive surgical techniques.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] The 1930s marked the beginning of the era of better surgical techniques as well as the first use of alloys such as vitallium.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Hench and others discovered that various kinds of glasses and ceramics could bond to living bone.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Hench was inspired by the idea on his way to a conference on materials.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] He was seated next to a colonel who had just returned from the Vietnam War.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] The colonel shared that after an injury the bodies of soldiers would often reject the implant.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Hench was intrigued and began to investigate materials that would be biocompatible.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] The final product was a new material which he called bioglass.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] This work inspired a new field called bioceramics.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] With the discovery of bioglass, interest in bioceramics grew rapidly.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] On April 26, 1988, the first international symposium on bioceramics was held in Kyoto, Japan.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Ceramics are now commonly used as dental and bone implants.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Joint replacements are commonly coated with bioceramic materials to reduce wear and inflammatory response.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Other examples of medical uses for bioceramics are in pacemakers, kidney dialysis machines, and respirators.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Bioceramics are meant to be used in extracorporeal circulation systems (kidney dialysis, for example) or engineered bioreactors; however, they are most common as implants.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Ceramics show numerous applications as biomaterials due to their physico-chemical properties.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] They have the advantage of being inert in the human body, and their hardness and resistance to abrasion makes them useful for bone and tooth replacement.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Some ceramics also have excellent resistance to friction, making them useful as replacement materials for malfunctioning joints.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Properties such as appearance and electrical insulation are also a concern for specific biomedical applications.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Some bioceramics incorporate alumina (Al2O3) as their lifespan is longer than that of the patient's.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] The material can be used in middle ear ossicles, ocular prostheses, electrical insulation for pacemakers, catheter orifices and in numerous prototypes of implantable systems such as cardiac pumps.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Aluminosilicates are commonly used in dental prostheses, pure or in ceramic-polymer composites.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] The ceramic-polymer composites are a potential way to fill cavities, replacing amalgams suspected to have toxic effects.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] The aluminosilicates also have a glassy structure.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Unlike artificial teeth in resin, the colour of tooth ceramic remains stable.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Zirconia doped with yttrium oxide has been proposed as a substitute for alumina for osteoarticular prostheses.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] The main advantages are a greater failure strength, and a good resistance to fatigue.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Vitreous carbon is also used as it is light, resistant to wear, and compatible with blood.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] It is mostly used in cardiac valve replacement.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Diamond can be used for the same application, but in coating form.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Calcium phosphate-based ceramics constitute, at present, the preferred bone substitute material in orthopaedic and maxillofacial applications, as they are similar to the main mineral phase of bone in structure and chemical composition.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Such synthetic bone substitute or scaffold materials are typically porous, which provides an increased surface area that encourages osseointegration, involving cell colonisation and revascularisation.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] However, such porous materials generally exhibit lower mechanical strength compared to bone, making highly porous implants very delicate.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Since the elastic modulus values of ceramic materials are generally higher than that of the surrounding bone tissue, the implant can cause mechanical stresses at the bone interface.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Calcium phosphates usually found in bioceramics include hydroxyapatite (HAP) Ca10(PO4)6(OH)2; tricalcium phosphate β (β TCP): Ca3 (PO4)2; and mixtures of HAP and β TCP.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] A number of implanted ceramics have not actually been designed for specific biomedical applications.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] However, they manage to find their way into different implantable systems because of their properties and their good biocompatibility.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Among these ceramics, we can cite silicon carbide, titanium nitrides and carbides, and boron nitride.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] TiN has been suggested as the friction surface in hip prostheses.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] While cell culture tests show a good biocompatibility, the analysis of implants shows significant wear, related to a delaminating of the TiN layer.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Silicon carbide is another modern-day ceramic which seems to provide good biocompatibility and can be used in bone implants.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] In addition to being used for their traditional properties, bioactive ceramics have seen specific use for due to their biological activity.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Calcium phosphates, oxides, and hydroxides are common examples.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Composites can be differentiated as bioresorbable or non-bioresorbable, with the latter being the result of the combination of a bioresorbable calcium phosphate (HAP) with a non-bioresorbable polymer (PMMA, PE).
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] These materials may become more widespread in the future, on account of the many combination possibilities and their aptitude at combining a biological activity with mechanical properties similar to those of the bone.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Bioceramics' properties of being anticorrosive, biocompatible, and aesthetic make them quite suitable for medical usage.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Zirconia ceramic has bioinertness and noncytotoxicity.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Carbon is another alternative with similar mechanical properties to bone, and it also features blood compatibility, no tissue reaction, and non-toxicity to cells.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Bioinert ceramics do not exhibit bonding with the bone, known as osseointegration.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] However, bioactivity of bioinert ceramics can be achieved by forming composites with bioactive ceramics.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Bioactive ceramics, including bioglasses must be non-toxic, and form a bond with bone.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] In bone repair applications, i.e. scaffolds for bone regeneration, the solubility of bioceramics is an important parameter, and the slow dissolution rate of most bioceramics relative to bone growth rates remains a challenge in their remedial usage.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Unsurprisingly, much focus is placed on improving dissolution characteristics of bioceramics while maintaining or improving their mechanical properties.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Glass ceramics elicit osteoinductive properties, with higher dissolution rates relative to crystalline materials, while crystalline calcium phosphate ceramics also exhibit non-toxicity to tissues and bioresorption.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] The ceramic particulate reinforcement has led to the choice of more materials for implant applications that include ceramic/ceramic, ceramic/polymer, and ceramic/metal composites.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Among these composites ceramic/polymer composites have been found to release toxic elements into the surrounding tissues.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Metals face corrosion related problems, and ceramic coatings on metallic implants degrade over time during lengthy applications.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Ceramic/ceramic composites enjoy superiority due to similarity to bone minerals, exhibiting biocompatibility and a readiness to be shaped.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] The biological activity of bioceramics has to be considered under various *in vitro* and *in vivo* studies.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Performance needs must be considered in accordance with the particular site of implantation.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Technically, ceramics are composed of raw materials such as powders and natural or synthetic chemical additives, favouring either compaction (hot, cold or isostatic), setting (hydraulic or chemical), or accelerating sintering processes.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] According to the formulation and shaping process used, bioceramics can vary in density and porosity as cements, ceramic depositions, or ceramic composites.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Porosity is often desired in bioceramics including bioglasses.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Towards improving the performance of transplanted porous bioceramics, numerous processing techniques are available for the control of porosity, pore size distribution and pore alignment.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] For crystalline materials, grain size and crystalline defects provide further pathways to enhance biodegradation and osseointegration, which are key for effective bone graft and bone transplant materials.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] This can be achieved by the inclusion of grain refining dopants and by imparting defects in the crystalline structure through various physical means.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] A developing material processing technique based on the biomimetic processes aims to imitate natural and biological processes and offer the possibility of making bioceramics at ambient temperature rather than through conventional or hydrothermal processes [GRO 96].
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] The prospect of using these relatively low processing temperatures opens up possibilities for mineral organic combinations with improved biological properties through the addition of proteins and biologically active molecules (growth factors, antibiotics, anti-tumor agents, etc.).
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] However, these materials have poor mechanical properties which can be improved, partially, by combining them with bonding proteins.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Common bioactive materials available commercially for clinical use include 45S5 bioactive glass, A/W bioactive glass ceramic, dense synthetic HA, and bioactive composites such as a polyethylene–HA mixture.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] All these materials form an interfacial bond with adjacent tissue.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] High-purity alumina bioceramics are currently commercially available from various producers.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] U.K. manufacturer Morgan Advanced Ceramics (MAC) began manufacturing orthopaedic devices in 1985 and quickly became a recognised supplier of ceramic femoral heads for hip replacements.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] MAC Bioceramics has the longest clinical history for alumina ceramic materials, manufacturing HIP Vitox® alumina since 1985.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Some calcium-deficient phosphates with an apatite structure were thus commercialised as "tricalcium phosphate" even though they did not exhibit the expected crystalline structure of tricalcium phosphate.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Currently, numerous commercial products described as HA are available in various physical forms (e.g. granules, specially designed blocks for specific applications).
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] HA/polymer composite (HA/polyethyelene, HAPEXTM) is also commercially available for ear implants, abrasives, and plasma-sprayed coating for orthopedic and dental implants.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Bioceramics are also been used in cannabis or delta 8 devices as wicks for the vaporization of such extracts.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Bioceramics have been proposed as a possible treatment for cancer.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Two methods of treatment have been proposed: hyperthermia and radiotherapy.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Hyperthermia treatment involves implanting a bioceramic material that contains a ferrite or other magnetic material.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] The area is then exposed to an alternating magnetic field, which causes the implant and surrounding area to heat up.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Alternatively, the bioceramic materials can be doped with β-emitting materials and implanted into the cancerous area.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Other trends include engineering bioceramics for specific tasks.
[src:biomaterials/bioceramic] Ongoing research involves the chemistry, composition, and micro- and nanostructures of the materials to improve their biocompatibility.
[src:biomaterials/biocompatibility] Since the immune response and repair functions in the body are so complicated it is not adequate to describe the biocompatibility of a single material in relation to a single cell type or tissue.
[src:biomaterials/biocompatibility] Sometimes one hears of biocompatibility testing that is a large battery of in vitro test that is used in accordance with ISO 10993 (or other similar standards) to determine if a certain material (or rather biomedical product) is biocompatible.
[src:biomaterials/biocompatibility] Research results have concluded that during performing in vitro cytotoxicity testing of biomaterials, "the authors should carefully specify the conditions of the test and comparison of different studies should be carried out with caution".
[src:biomaterials/biocompatibility] The word *biocompatibility* was mentioned for the first time in peer-review journals and meetings in 1970 by RJ Hegyeli (Amer Chem Soc Annual Meeting abstract) and CA Homsy.
[src:biomaterials/biocompatibility] It took almost two decades before it began to be commonly used in scientific literature.
[src:biomaterials/biocompatibility] Recently, Williams has been trying to reevaluate the current knowledge status regarding what factors determine clinical success.
[src:biomaterials/biocompatibility] Doing so notes that an implant may not always have to be positively bioactive but it must not do any harm (either locally or systemically).
[src:biomaterials/biocompatibility] "The ability of a material to perform with an appropriate host response in a specific application", Williams' definition.
[src:biomaterials/biocompatibility] "Biocompatibility is the capability of a prosthesis implanted in the body to exist in harmony with tissue without causing deleterious changes".
[src:biomaterials/biocompatibility] This is also called the “Williams definition” or “William's definition”.
[src:biomaterials/biocompatibility] It was defined in the European Society for Biomaterials Consensus Conference I and can more easily be found in ‘The Williams Dictionary of Biomaterials’.
[src:biomaterials/biocompatibility] The ASTM is not recommended according to Williams Dictionary since it only refers to local tissue responses, in animal models.
[src:biomaterials/biocompatibility] The fourth is an expansion or rather more precise version of the first definition noting both that low toxicity and the one should be aware of the different demands between various medical applications of the same material.
[src:biomaterials/biocompatibility] All these definitions deal with materials and not with devices.
[src:biomaterials/biocompatibility] This is a drawback since many medical devices are made of more than one material.
[src:biomaterials/biocompatibility] Much of the pre-clinical testing of the materials is not conducted on the devices but rather the material itself.
[src:biomaterials/biocompatibility] But at some stage the testing will have to include the device since the shape, geometry and surface treatment etc. of the device will also affect its biocompatibility.
[src:biomaterials/biocompatibility] In the literature, one quite often stumbles upon the adjective form, ‘biocompatible’.
[src:biomaterials/biocompatibility] However, according to Williams’ definition, this does not make any sense because biocompatibility is contextual, i.e. much more than just the material itself will determine the clinical outcome of the medical device of which the biomaterial is a part.
[src:biomaterials/biocompatibility] This also points to one of the weaknesses with the current definition because a medical device usually is made of more than one material.
[src:biomaterials/biocompatibility] Biocompatibility (or tissue compatibility) describes the ability of a material to perform with an appropriate host response when applied as intended.
[src:biomaterials/biocompatibility] A biocompatible material may not be completely "inert"; in fact, the appropriateness of the host response is decisive.
[src:biomaterials/biocompatibility] The scope of the first definition is so wide that D Williams tried to find suitable subgroups of applications in order to be able to make more narrow definitions.
[src:biomaterials/biocompatibility] The biocompatibility of a long-term implantable medical device refers to the ability of the device to perform its intended function, with the desired degree of incorporation in the host, without eliciting any undesirable local or systemic effects in that host.
[src:biomaterials/biocompatibility] In these definitions the notion of biocompatibility is related to devices rather than to materials as compared to top three definitions.
[src:biomaterials/biocompatibility] There was a consensus conference on biomaterial definitions in Sorrento September 15–16, 2005.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] A **biomaterial** is a substance that has been engineered to interact with biological systems for a medical purpose – either a therapeutic (treat, augment, repair, or replace a tissue function of the body) or a diagnostic one.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The corresponding field of study is called **biomaterials science** or **biomaterials engineering**.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] It has experienced steady growth over its history, with many companies investing large amounts of money into the development of new products.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Biomaterials science encompasses elements of medicine, biology, chemistry, tissue engineering and materials science.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] A biomaterial is different from a biological material, such as bone, that is produced by a biological system.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] However, "biomaterial" and "biological material" are often used interchangeably.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Further, the word "bioterial" has been proposed as a potential alternate word for biologically produced materials such as bone, or fungal biocomposites.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Additionally, care should be exercised in defining a biomaterial as biocompatible, since it is application-specific.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] A biomaterial that is biocompatible or suitable for one application may not be biocompatible in another.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Nanobiomaterials are a specialization of nanomaterials; nanobiomaterials are biomaterials in the nanoscale typically used in the field of nanomedicine since they can both actively interact with biological systems and mimic biological structures.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Biomaterials can be derived either from nature or synthesized in the laboratory using a variety of chemical approaches utilizing metallic components, polymers, ceramics or composite materials.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] They are often used and/or adapted for a medical application, and thus comprise the whole or part of a living structure or biomedical device which performs, augments, or replaces a natural function.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Such functions may be relatively passive, like being used for a heart valve, or may be bioactive with a more interactive functionality, such as hydroxy-apatite coated hip implants.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Biomaterials are also commonly used in dental applications, surgery, and drug delivery.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] For example, a construct with impregnated pharmaceutical products can be placed into the body, which permits the prolonged release of a drug over an extended period of time.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] A biomaterial may also be an autograft, allograft or xenograft used as a transplant material.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The Biomaterials science has become one of the most multi-disciplinary fields of all sciences as it involves different stakeholders from engineers, chemists, physicians, biochemists, clinicians and other more.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] This field is still expanding along with the discoveries made in the field.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The term biomaterial is still relatively new as it did not exist 60 years ago.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Biomaterials are crucially needed as they are getting more and more important as they are employed in different clinical applications such as skeletal systems, tissue engineering, dentistry and orthopedics.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The ability of an engineered biomaterial to induce a physiological response that is supportive of the biomaterial's function and performance is known as bioactivity.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Most commonly, in bioactive glasses and bioactive ceramics this term refers to the ability of implanted materials to bond well with surrounding tissue in either osteo conductive or osseo productive roles.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Bone implant materials are often designed to promote bone growth while dissolving into surrounding body fluid.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Thus for many biomaterials good biocompatibility along with good strength and dissolution rates are desirable.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Commonly, bioactivity of biomaterials is gauged by the surface biomineralization in which a native layer of hydroxyapatite is formed at the surface.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] These days, the development of clinically useful biomaterials is greatly enhanced by the advent of computational routines that can predict the molecular effects of biomaterials in a therapeutic setting based on limited *in vitro* experimentation.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Self-assembly is the most common term in use in the modern scientific community to describe the spontaneous aggregation of particles (atoms, molecules, colloids, micelles, etc.) without the influence of any external forces.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Large groups of such particles are known to assemble themselves into thermodynamically stable, structurally well-defined arrays, quite reminiscent of one of the seven crystal systems found in metallurgy and mineralogy (e.g., face-centered cubic, body-centered cubic, etc.).
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The fundamental difference in equilibrium structure is in the spatial scale of the unit cell (lattice parameter) in each particular case.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Molecular self assembly is found widely in biological systems and provides the basis of a wide variety of complex biological structures.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] This includes an emerging class of mechanically superior biomaterials based on microstructural features and designs found in nature.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Thus, self-assembly is also emerging as a new strategy in chemical synthesis and nanotechnology.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Molecular crystals, liquid crystals, colloids, micelles, emulsions, phase-separated polymers, thin films and self-assembled monolayers all represent examples of the types of highly ordered structures, which are obtained using these techniques.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The distinguishing feature of these methods is self-organization.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Nearly all materials could be seen as hierarchically structured, since the changes in spatial scale bring about different mechanisms of deformation and damage.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] However, in biological materials, this hierarchical organization is inherent to the microstructure.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] One of the first examples of this, in the history of structural biology, is the early X-ray scattering work on the hierarchical structure of hair and wool by Astbury and Woods.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] In bone, for example, collagen is the building block of the organic matrix, a triple helix with diameter of 1.5 nm.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] These tropocollagen molecules are intercalated with the mineral phase (hydroxyapatite, calcium phosphate) forming fibrils that curl into helicoids of alternating directions.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] These "osteons" are the basic building blocks of bones, with the volume fraction distribution between organic and mineral phase being about 60/40.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] In another level of complexity, the hydroxyapatite crystals are mineral platelets that have a diameter of approximately 70 to 100 nm and thickness of 1 nm.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] They originally nucleate at the gaps between collagen fibrils.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Similarly, the hierarchy of abalone shell begins at the nanolevel, with an organic layer having a thickness of 20 to 30 nm.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] This layer proceeds with single crystals of aragonite (a polymorph of CaCO3) consisting of "bricks" with dimensions of 0.5 and finishing with layers approximately 0.3 mm (mesostructure).
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Crabs are arthropods, whose carapace is made of a mineralized hard component (exhibits brittle fracture) and a softer organic component composed primarily of chitin.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The brittle component is arranged in a helical pattern.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Each of these mineral "rods" (1 μm diameter) contains chitin–protein fibrils with approximately 60 nm diameter.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] These fibrils are made of 3 nm diameter canals that link the interior and exterior of the shell.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Biomaterials must be compatible with the body, and there are often issues of biocompatibility, which must be resolved before a product can be placed on the market and used in a clinical setting.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Because of this, biomaterials are usually subjected to the same requirements as those undergone by new drug therapies.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] All manufacturing companies are also required to ensure traceability of all of their products, so that if a defective product is discovered, others in the same batch may be traced.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Calcium sulfate (its α- and β-hemihydrates) is a well known biocompatible material that is widely used as a bone graft substitute in dentistry or as its binder, in orthopedic applications such as fractures, osteomyelitis and congenital diseases, in tissue engineering and spinal applications.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] In the United States, 49% of the 250,000 valve replacement procedures performed annually involve a mechanical valve implant.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The most widely used valve is a bileaflet disc heart valve or St.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The mechanics involve two semicircular discs moving back and forth, with both allowing the flow of blood as well as the ability to form a seal against backflow.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The valve is coated with pyrolytic carbon and secured to the surrounding tissue with a mesh of woven fabric called Dacron (du Pont's trade name for polyethylene terephthalate).
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The mesh allows for the body's tissue to grow, while incorporating the valve.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Most of the time, artificial tissue is grown from the patient's own cells.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] However, when the damage is so extreme that it is impossible to use the patient's own cells, artificial tissue cells are grown.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The difficulty is in finding a scaffold that the cells can grow and organize on.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The characteristics of the scaffold must be that it is biocompatible, cells can adhere to the scaffold, mechanically strong and biodegradable.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] One successful scaffold is a copolymer of lactic acid and glycolic acid.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] As discussed previously, biomaterials are used in medical devices to treat, assist, or replace a function within the human body.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The application of a specific biomaterial must combine the necessary composition, material properties, structure, and desired in vivo reaction in order to perform the desired function.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Categorizations of different desired properties are defined in order to maximize functional results.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Host response is defined as the "response of the host organism (local and systemic) to the implanted material or device".
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Most materials will have a reaction when in contact with the human body.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The success of a biomaterial relies on the host tissue's reaction with the foreign material.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Specific reactions between the host tissue and the biomaterial can be generated through the biocompatibility of the material.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The in vivo functionality and longevity of any implantable medical device is affected by the body's response to the foreign material.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The body undergoes a cascade of processes defined under the foreign body response (FBR) in order to protect the host from the foreign material.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The interactions between the device upon the host tissue/blood as well as the host tissue/blood upon the device must be understood in order to prevent complications and device failure.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Tissue injury caused by device implantation causes inflammatory and healing responses during FBR.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The inflammatory response occurs within two time periods: the acute phase, and the chronic phase.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The acute phase occurs during the initial hours to days of implantation, and is identified by fluid and protein exudation along with a neutrophilic reaction.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] During the acute phase, the body attempts to clean and heal the wound by delivering excess blood, proteins, and monocytes are called to the site.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Continued inflammation leads to the chronic phase, which can be categorized by the presence of monocytes, macrophages, and lymphocytes.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] In addition, blood vessels and connective tissue form in order to heal the wounded area.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Biocompatibility is related to the behavior of biomaterials in various environments under various chemical and physical conditions.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The term may refer to specific properties of a material without specifying where or how the material is to be used.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] For example, a material may elicit little or no immune response in a given organism, and may or may not able to integrate with a particular cell type or tissue.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Immuno-informed biomaterial that direct the immune response rather than attempting to circumvent the process is one approach that shows promise.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The ambiguity of the term reflects the ongoing development of insights into "how biomaterials interact with the human body" and eventually "how those interactions determine the clinical success of a medical device (such as pacemaker or hip replacement)".
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Modern medical devices and prostheses are often made of more than one material, so it might not always be sufficient to talk about the biocompatibility of a specific material.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Surgical implantation of a biomaterial into the body triggers an organism-inflammatory reaction with the associated healing of the damaged tissue.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Depending upon the composition of the implanted material, the surface of the implant, the mechanism of fatigue, and chemical decomposition there are several other reactions possible.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] These include immune response, foreign body reaction with the isolation of the implant with a vascular connective tissue, possible infection, and impact on the lifespan of the implant.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Graft-versus-host disease is an auto- and alloimmune disorder, exhibiting a variable clinical course.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] It can manifest in either acute or chronic form, affecting multiple organs and tissues and causing serious complications in clinical practice, both during transplantation and implementation of biocompatible materials.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] A biomaterial should perform its intended function within the living body without negatively affecting other bodily tissues and organs.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] In order to prevent unwanted organ and tissue interactions, biomaterials should be non-toxic.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The toxicity of a biomaterial refers to the substances that are emitted from the biomaterial while in vivo.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] A biomaterial should not give off anything to its environment unless it is intended to do so.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Nontoxicity means that biomaterial is: noncarcinogenic, nonpyrogenic, hypoallergenic, blood compatible, and noninflammatory.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] However, a biomaterial can be designed to include toxicity for an intended purpose.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] For example, application of toxic biomaterial is studied during in vivo and in vitro cancer immunotherapy testing.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Toxic biomaterials offer an opportunity to manipulate and control cancer cells.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] One recent study states: "Advanced nanobiomaterials, including liposomes, polymers, and silica, play a vital role in the codelivery of drugs and immunomodulators.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] These nanobiomaterial-based delivery systems could effectively promote antitumor immune responses and simultaneously reduce toxic adverse effects." This is a prime example of how the biocompatibility of a biomaterial can be altered to produce any desired function.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Biodegradable biomaterials refers to materials that are degradable through natural enzymatic reactions.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The application of biodegradable synthetic polymers began in the later 1960s.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Biodegradable materials have an advantage over other materials, as they have lower risk of harmful effects long term.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] In addition to ethical advancements using biodegradable materials, they also improve biocompatibility for materials used for implantation.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Several properties including biocompatibility are important when considering different biodegradable biomaterials.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Biodegradable biomaterials can be synthetic or natural depending on their source and type of extracellular matrix (ECM).
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Some of the most commonly used biocompatible materials (or biomaterials) are polymers due to their inherent flexibility and tunable mechanical properties.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] To ensure biocompatibility, there are a series of regulated tests that material must pass to be certified for use.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] These include the United States Pharmacopoeia IV (USP Class IV) Biological Reactivity Test and the International Standards Organization 10993 (ISO 10993) Biological Evaluation of Medical Devices.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The main objective of biocompatibility tests is to quantify the acute and chronic toxicity of material and determine any potential adverse effects during use conditions, thus the tests required for a given material are dependent on its end-use (i.e. blood, central nervous system, etc.).
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Two properties that have a large effect on the functionality of a biomaterial is the *surface* and *bulk properties*.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] In addition to a material being certified as biocompatible, biomaterials must be engineered specifically to their target application within a medical device.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] This is especially important in terms of mechanical properties which govern the way that a given biomaterial behaves.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] One of the most relevant material parameters is the Young's Modulus, *E*, which describes a material's elastic response to stresses.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The Young's Moduli of the tissue and the device that is being coupled to it must closely match for optimal compatibility between device and body, whether the device is implanted or mounted externally.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Matching the elastic modulus makes it possible to limit movement and delamination at the biointerface between implant and tissue as well as avoiding stress concentration that can lead to mechanical failure.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Other important properties are the tensile and compressive strengths which quantify the maximum stresses a material can withstand before breaking and may be used to set stress limits that a device may be subject to within or external to the body.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Depending on the application, it may be desirable for a biomaterial to have high strength so that it is resistant to failure when subjected to a load, however in other applications it may be beneficial for the material to be low strength.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] There is a careful balance between strength and stiffness that determines how robust to failure the biomaterial device is.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Typically, as the elasticity of the biomaterial increases, the ultimate tensile strength will decrease and vice versa.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] When this happens, irreversible damage to the brain can occur, thus the biomaterial must have an elastic modulus less than or equal to brain tissue and a low tensile strength if an applied load is expected.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] For implanted biomaterials that may experience temperature fluctuations, e.g., dental implants, ductility is important.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The material must be ductile for a similar reason that the tensile strength cannot be too high, ductility allows the material to bend without fracture and also prevents the concentration of stresses in the tissue when the temperature changes.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The material property of toughness is also important for dental implants as well as any other rigid, load-bearing implant such as a replacement hip joint.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] For medical devices that are implanted or attached to the skin, another important property requiring consideration is the flexural rigidity, *D*.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Since flexural rigidity depends on the thickness of the material, *h*, to the third power (*h*3), it is very important that a biomaterial can be formed into thin layers in the previously mentioned applications where conformality is paramount.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The molecular composition of a biomaterial determines the physical and chemical properties of a biomaterial.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] These compositions create complex structures that allow the biomaterial to function, and therefore are necessary to define and understand in order to develop a biomaterial. biomaterials can be designed to replicate natural organisms, a process known as biomimetics.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The structure of a biomaterial can be observed at different levels to better understand a materials properties and function.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The arrangement of atoms and ions within a material is one of the most important structural properties of a biomaterial.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The atomic structure of a material can be viewed at different levels, the sub atomic level, atomic or molecular level, as well as the ultra-structure created by the atoms and molecules.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Intermolecular forces between the atoms and molecules that compose the material will determine its material and chemical properties.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The sub atomic level observes the electrical structure of an individual atom to define its interactions with other atoms and molecules.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The molecular structure observes the arrangement of atoms within the material.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Finally the ultra-structure observes the 3-D structure created from the atomic and molecular structures of the material.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The solid-state of a material is characterized by the intramolecular bonds between the atoms and molecules that comprise the material.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Types of intramolecular bonds include: ionic bonds, covalent bonds, and metallic bonds.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] These bonds will dictate the physical and chemical properties of the material, as well as determine the type of material (ceramic, metal, or polymer).
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The microstructure of a material refers to the structure of an object, organism, or material as viewed at magnifications exceeding 25 times.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] It is composed of the different phases of form, size, and distribution of grains, pores, precipitates, etc.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The majority of solid microstructures are crystalline, however some materials such as certain polymers will not crystallize when in the solid state.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Crystalline structure is the composition of ions, atoms, and molecules that are held together and ordered in a 3D shape.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The main difference between a crystalline structure and an amorphous structure is the order of the components.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Crystalline has the highest level of order possible in the material where amorphous structure consists of irregularities in the ordering pattern.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] One way to describe crystalline structures is through the crystal lattice, which is a three-dimensional representation of the location of a repeating factor (unit cell) in the structure denoted with lattices.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] There are 14 different configurations of atom arrangement in a crystalline structure, and are all represented under Bravais lattices.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] During the formation of a crystalline structure, different impurities, irregularities, and other defects can form.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] These imperfections can form through deformation of the solid, rapid cooling, or high energy radiation.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Types of defects include point defects, line defects, as well as edge dislocation.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Macrostructure refers to the overall geometric properties that will influence the force at failure, stiffness, bending, stress distribution, and the weight of the material.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] It requires little to no magnification to reveal the macrostructure of a material.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Observing the macrostructure reveals properties such as cavities, porosity, gas bubbles, stratification, and fissures.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] The material's strength and elastic modulus are both independent of the macrostructure.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Biomaterials can be constructed using only materials sourced from plants and animals in order to alter, replace, or repair human tissue/organs.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Use of natural biomaterials were used as early as ancient Egypt, where indigenous people used animal skin as sutures.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] A more modern example is a hip replacement using ivory material which was first recorded in Germany 1891.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Biopolymers are polymers produced by living organisms.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Cellulose and starch, proteins and peptides, and DNA and RNA are all examples of biopolymers, in which the monomeric units, respectively, are sugars, amino acids, and nucleotides.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] Cellulose is both the most common biopolymer and the most common organic compound on Earth.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] About 33% of all plant matter is cellulose.
[src:biomaterials/biomaterial] On a similar manner, silk (proteinaceous biopolymer) has garnered tremendous research interest in a myriad of domains including tissue engineering and regenerative medicine, microfluidics, drug delivery.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] A **foreign body reaction** (**FBR**) is a typical tissue response to a foreign body within biological tissue.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] It usually includes the formation of a **foreign body granuloma**.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Tissue encapsulation of an implant is an example, as is inflammation around a splinter.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Foreign body granuloma formation consists of protein adsorption, macrophages, multinucleated foreign body giant cells (macrophage fusion), fibroblasts, and angiogenesis.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] It has also been proposed that the mechanical property of the interface between an implant and its surrounding tissues is critical for the host response.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] In the long term, the foreign body reaction results in encapsulation of the foreign body within a calcified shell.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] For example, a *lithopedion* is a rare phenomenon which occurs most commonly when a fetus dies during an abdominal pregnancy, is too large to be reabsorbed by the body, and calcifies.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Following biomaterial implantation, blood and body fluids contact the implant surface.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Host blood proteins adsorb onto the implant surface and a fibrin matrix forms.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Acute and chronic inflammation follow the initial blood protein deposition and matrix formation.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Macrophages at the implant site fuse to form foreign body giant cells.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Following the inflammatory response, granulation tissue form.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] The end stage of the foreign body reaction is the fibrous capsule formation around the implanted biomaterial.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] The biocompatibility of the device affects the severity of the foreign body reaction.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] The foreign body reaction can lead to device failure.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] During blood-biomaterial interaction, blood proteins spontaneously adsorb to the biomaterial surface.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] The biomaterial surface properties affect the types, concentrations, and conformation of proteins that adsorb to the surface.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] The Vroman effect can describe the time-dependent behavior of this protein adsorption.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Surface-adsorbed proteins regulate inflammatory cell interaction and adhesion.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] The deposited proteins allow inflammatory cells to attach via integrins.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] The biomaterial surface can also recruit and activate complement proteins.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] The composition and conformation of adsorbed proteins on the implant surface is critical to the foreign body reaction.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] For the first two days, neutrophils are the primary cell type that deposit on the implant surface.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Neutrophils release degradative enzymes and reactive oxygen intermediates that damages the implant.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Platelets from the blood-biomaterial interaction release inflammatory cytokines that cause monocytes and macrophages to extravasate and migrate to the implant site.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] The degranulation and release of histamine from mast cells further recruits macrophages to the biomaterial.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Macrophages adhere to the biomaterial surface based on the surface protein deposits and produce cytokines that further recruit macrophages.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Foreign body granuloma forms as immune cells accumulate on the biomaterial surface in an attempt to eliminate the biomaterial.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Adherent macrophages at the implant site can fuse into a multinucleated cell called foreign body giant cell.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Foreign body giant cell formation depends on the biomaterial surface properties and on the presence of interleukin-4 and interleukin-13.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Foreign body giant cells release reactive oxygen intermediates, degradative enzymes, and acid onto the biomaterial surface.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Foreign body giant cells also attempt to engulf the biomaterial for degradation.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Adherent macrophages and foreign body giant cells degrade biomaterials and can lead to device failure.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Foreign body giant cells remain on the surface of the implanted device throughout the device's lifetime.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] The end-stage healing response is the fibrous encapsulation of the biomaterial.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Macrophages and foreign body giant cells release cytokines that attract fibroblasts.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Fibroblasts create a collagenous fibrous capsule to separate the biomaterial from the surrounding tissue.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] The fibrous capsule may hinder the device's function, such as drug diffusion for drug delivery systems or normal tissue regeneration for tissue engineering implants.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] The foreign body giant cell formation and the fibrous encapsulation of the implanted device can affect the function of the implanted device and lead to its failure.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Reducing the foreign body reaction can promote better device performance and durability.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Even though many types of implants cannot completely escape the foreign body reaction, there are many ways to engineer biomaterials to reduce the foreign body reaction.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Reducing nonspecific protein adsorption is one important method to prevent fibrous encapsulation of the implant.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] The physical properties of the implant's surface, such as size, shape, topology, and strength, influence protein adsorption and immune cell interactions with the implant.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Generally, surface roughness induces greater protein adsorption and triggers greater immune response.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Thicker cylindrical implants on the millimeter scale were shown to produce greater fibrous encapsulation.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] However, there may not be an absolute relationship between the modification of the biomaterial and the associated foreign body response, because some biomaterials intrinsically induce a stronger foreign body response than other biomaterials would.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Implanted biomaterial can be loaded with different drugs to perform anti-inflammatory functions or promote angiogenesis to further integrate the implant with the host.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] The sustained release of certain anti-inflammatory drugs from the biomaterial, such as dexamethasone, is shown to increase implant life by preventing inflammation and fibrosis.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Coating the implant surface with biomimetic biomaterial may reduce the foreign body reaction and reduce the device failure rate.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Biomaterials that mimic the extracellular matrix can significantly reduce the inflammatory response as well as reduce foreign body giant cell formation.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Developing materials that resist protein adsorption, fibrous encapsulation, or foreign body giant cell formation is important to resist the foreign body reaction.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Commonly used biomaterials like polyethylene glycol and polyhydroxyethylmethacrylate resist nonspecific protein adsorption but are easily degraded in the in vivo oxidative environment.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Therefore, scientists are looking for new materials that intrinsically resist the foreign body reaction.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Zwitterionic polymers are widely used in surface modification because they can inhibit non-specific protein adhesion.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Zwitterionic hydrogels also promote angiogenesis in surrounding tissues.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Commonly used zwitterionic materials include sulfobetaine, carboxybetaine, and phosphorylcholine.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Zwitterionic polymers have the ability to reduce nonspecific adsorption of proteins and cells at biological interfaces.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Zwitterionic coatings are often used to minimize the negative effects of foreign body response for implanted devices and improve the device's biocompatibility.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] The mechanism is related to surface charge balancing and creation of a strong hydration sphere.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Zwitterionic coatings can be covalently attached by "grafting to" and "grafting from" methods.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] With "grafting to" methods, the surface is modified with the polymer after synthesis, whereas with "grafting from" methods, polymer is directly synthesized on a modified surface.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Several "grafting to" methods have been used to covalently attach zwitterionic polymers to surfaces.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Anderson group developed attachment to the surface via polydopamine conjugation.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] In this case, copolymer should contain a thiol group.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Nazarova and coworkers synthesized MPC copolymers with 2-methacrylamido-D-glucose, N-vinylpyrrolidone, and N-vinyl-N-methyl-acetamide and grafted them onto the surface of carbon fibre biosorbent using γ-radiation.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] MPC copolymers with trimethoxysilylpropyl methacrylate can be thermally cured and self-crosslinked.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Alginates are widely used for their low cost, low toxicity, and tunability.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] However, implantation of only alginate will trigger serious foreign body reaction.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] There are a few triazole-containing alginate derivative microspheres that remain clear of fibrotic deposition in mice, but more studies are required to explore the relationship between triazole groups and the inflammatory response.
[src:biomaterials/foreign-body-reaction] Polyethylene glycol peptides and zwitterionic peptides have immunomodulatory functions that help to resist the foreign body reaction.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] An **implant** is a medical device manufactured to replace a missing biological structure, support a damaged biological structure, or enhance an existing biological structure.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] For example, an implant may be a rod, used to strengthen weak bones.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Medical implants are human-made devices, in contrast to a transplant, which is a transplanted biomedical tissue.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] The surface of implants that contact the body might be made of a biomedical material such as titanium, silicone, or apatite depending on what is the most functional.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] In 2018, for example, American Elements developed a nickel alloy powder for 3D printing robust, long-lasting, and biocompatible medical implants.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] In some cases implants contain electronics, e.g. artificial pacemaker and cochlear implants.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Some implants are bioactive, such as subcutaneous drug delivery devices in the form of implantable pills or drug-eluting stents.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Sensory and neurological implants are used for disorders affecting the major senses and the brain, as well as other neurological disorders.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Examples include the intraocular lens, intrastromal corneal ring segment, cochlear implant, tympanostomy tube, and neurostimulator.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Cardiovascular medical devices are implanted in cases where the heart, its valves, and the rest of the circulatory system is in disorder.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] They are used to treat conditions such as heart failure, cardiac arrhythmia, ventricular tachycardia, valvular heart disease, angina pectoris, and atherosclerosis.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Examples include the artificial heart, artificial heart valve, implantable cardioverter-defibrillator, artificial cardiac pacemaker, and coronary stent.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Orthopaedic implants help alleviate issues with the bones and joints of the body.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] They are used to treat bone fractures, osteoarthritis, scoliosis, spinal stenosis, and chronic pain as well as in knee and hip replacements.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Examples include a wide variety of pins, rods, screws, and plates used to anchor fractured bones while they heal.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Metallic glasses based on magnesium with zinc and calcium addition are tested as the potential metallic biomaterials for biodegradable medical implants.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Patients with orthopaedic implants sometimes need to be put under magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) machine for detailed musculoskeletal study.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Therefore, concerns have been raised regarding the loosening and migration of implant, heating of the implant metal which could cause thermal damage to surrounding tissues, and distortion of the MRI scan that affects the imaging results.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] A study of orthopaedic implants in 2005 has shown that majority of the orthopaedic implants does not react with magnetic fields under the 1.0 Tesla MRI scanning machine with the exception of external fixator clamps.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] However, at 7.0 Tesla, several orthopaedic implants would show significant interaction with the MRI magnetic fields, such as heel and fibular implant.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Electrical implants are being used to relieve pain from rheumatoid arthritis.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] The electric implant is embedded in the neck of patients with rheumatoid arthritis, the implant sends electrical signals to electrodes in the vagus nerve.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] The application of this device is being tested an alternative to medicating people with rheumatoid arthritis for their lifetime.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Contraceptive implants are primarily used to prevent unintended pregnancy and treat conditions such as non-pathological forms of menorrhagia.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Examples include copper- and hormone-based intrauterine and subcutaneous devices .
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Cosmetic implants — often prosthetics — attempt to bring some portion of the body back to an acceptable aesthetic norm.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] They are used as a follow-up to mastectomy due to breast cancer, for correcting some forms of disfigurement, and modifying aspects of the body (as in buttock augmentation and chin augmentation).
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Examples include the breast implant, nose prosthesis, ocular prosthesis, and injectable filler.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Other types of organ dysfunction can occur in the systems of the body, including the gastrointestinal, respiratory, and urological systems.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Implants are used in those and other locations to treat conditions such as gastroesophageal reflux disease, gastroparesis, respiratory failure, sleep apnea, urinary and fecal incontinence, and erectile dysfunction.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Examples include the LINX, implantable gastric stimulator, diaphragmatic/phrenic nerve stimulator, neurostimulator, surgical mesh, artificial urinary sphincter and penile implant.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Drug‑eluting implants combine the structural benefits of traditional devices with advanced drug delivery systems, resulting in controlled release through the use of specialized materials.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] These implants often utilise biodegradable polymers—such as PLA, PGA, and PLGA for the controlled release of medications through the use of mechanisms like diffusion, polymer degradation, and osmotic pressure, ensuring high local concentrations while minimizing systemic side effects.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Medical devices are classified by the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) under three different classes depending on the risks the medical device may impose on the user.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] According to 21CFR 860.3, Class I devices are considered to pose the least amount of risk to the user and require the least amount of control.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Class I devices include simple devices such as arm slings and hand-held surgical instruments.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Class II devices are considered to need more regulation than Class I devices and are required to undergo specific requirements before FDA approval.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Class II devices include X-ray systems and physiological monitors.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Class III devices require the most regulatory controls since the device supports or sustains human life or may not be well tested.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Class III devices include replacement heart valves and implanted cerebellar stimulators.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Many implants typically fall under Class II and Class III devices.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] A variety of minimally bioreactive metals are routinely implanted.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] The most commonly implanted form of stainless steel is 316L.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Cobalt-chromium and titanium-based implant alloys are also permanently implanted.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] All of these are made passive by a thin layer of oxide on their surface.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] A consideration, however, is that metal ions diffuse outward through the oxide and end up in the surrounding tissue.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Bioreaction to metal implants includes the formation of a small envelope of fibrous tissue.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] The thickness of this layer is determined by the products being dissolved, and the extent to which the implant moves around within the enclosing tissue.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Pure titanium may have only a minimal fibrous encapsulation.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Stainless steel, on the other hand, may elicit encapsulation of as much as 2 mm.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Porous implants are characterized by the presence of voids in the metallic or ceramic matrix.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Voids can be regular, such as in additively manufactured (AM) lattices, or stochastic, such as in gas-infiltrated production processes.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] The reduction in the modulus of the implant follows a complex nonlinear relationship dependent on the volume fraction of base material and morphology of the pores.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Experimental models exist to predict the range of modulus that stochastic porous material may take.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Above 10% vol. fraction porosity, models begin to deviate significantly.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Different models, such as the rule of mixtures for low porosity, two-material matrices have been developed to describe mechanical properties.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] AM lattices have more predictable mechanical properties compared to stochastic porous materials and can be tuned such that they have favorable directional mechanical properties.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Variables such as strut diameter, strut shape, and number of cross-beams can have a dramatic effect on loading characteristics of the lattice.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] AM has the ability to fine-tune the lattice spacing to within a much smaller range than stochastically porous structures, enabling the future cell-development of specific cultures in tissue engineering.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] 1) The elastic modulus of the implant is decreased, allowing the implant to better match the elastic modulus of the bone.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] 2) Porosity enables osteoblastic cells to grow into the pores of implants.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Cells can span gaps of smaller than 75 microns and grow into pores larger than 200 microns.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Bone ingrowth is a favorable effect, as it anchors the cells into the implant, increasing the strength of the bone-implant interface.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] More load is transferred from the implant to the bone, reducing stress shielding effects.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] The density of the bone around the implant is likely to be higher due to the increased load applied to the bone.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Bone ingrowth reduces the likelihood of the implant loosening over time because stress shielding and corresponding bone resorption over extended timescales is avoided.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Porosity of greater than 40% is favourable to facilitate sufficient anchoring of the osteoblastic cells.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Under ideal conditions, implants should initiate the desired host response.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Ideally, the implant should not cause any undesired reaction from neighbouring or distant tissues.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] However, the interaction between the implant and the tissue surrounding the implant can lead to complications.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] The process of implantation of medical devices is subjected to the same complications that other invasive medical procedures can have during or after surgery.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Common complications include infection, inflammation, and pain.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Other complications that can occur include risk of rejection from implant-induced coagulation and allergic foreign body response.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Depending on the type of implant, the complications may vary.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] When the site of an implant becomes infected during or after surgery, the surrounding tissue becomes infected by microorganisms.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Three main categories of infection can occur after operation.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Superficial immediate infections are caused by organisms that commonly grow near or on skin.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] The infection usually occurs at the surgical opening.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Deep immediate infection, the second type, occurs immediately after surgery at the site of the implant.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Skin-dwelling and airborne bacteria cause deep immediate infection.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] These bacteria enter the body by attaching to the implant's surface prior to implantation.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Though not common, deep immediate infections can also occur from dormant bacteria from previous infections of the tissue at the implantation site that have been activated from being disturbed during the surgery.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] The last type, late infection, occurs months to years after the implantation of the implant.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Late infections are caused by dormant blood-borne bacteria attached to the implant prior to implantation.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] The blood-borne bacteria colonize on the implant and eventually get released from it.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Depending on the type of material used to make the implant, it may be infused with antibiotics to lower the risk of infections during surgery.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] However, only certain types of materials can be infused with antibiotics, the use of antibiotic-infused implants runs the risk of rejection by the patient since the patient may develop a sensitivity to the antibiotic, and the antibiotic may not work on the bacteria.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Inflammation, a common occurrence after any surgical procedure, is the body's response to tissue damage as a result of trauma, infection, intrusion of foreign materials, or local cell death, or as a part of an immune response.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Inflammation starts with the rapid dilation of local capillaries to supply the local tissue with blood.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] The inflow of blood causes the tissue to become swollen and may cause cell death.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] The excess blood, or edema, can activate pain receptors at the tissue.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] The site of the inflammation becomes warm from local disturbances of fluid flow and the increased cellular activity to repair the tissue or remove debris from the site.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Implant-induced coagulation is similar to the coagulation process done within the body to prevent blood loss from damaged blood vessels.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] However, the coagulation process is triggered from proteins that become attached to the implant surface and lose their shapes.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] When this occurs, the protein changes conformation and different activation sites become exposed, which may trigger an immune system response where the body attempts to attack the implant to remove the foreign material.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] The trigger of the immune system response can be accompanied by inflammation.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] The immune system response may lead to chronic inflammation where the implant is rejected and has to be removed from the body.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] The immune system may encapsulate the implant as an attempt to remove the foreign material from the site of the tissue by encapsulating the implant in fibrinogen and platelets.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] The encapsulation of the implant can lead to further complications, since the thick layers of fibrous encapsulation may prevent the implant from performing the desired functions.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Bacteria may attack the fibrous encapsulation and become embedded into the fibers.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Since the layers of fibres are thick, antibiotics may not be able to reach the bacteria and the bacteria may grow and infect the surrounding tissue.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] In order to remove the bacteria, the implant would have to be removed.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Lastly, the immune system may accept the presence of the implant and repair and remodel the surrounding tissue.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Similar responses occur when the body initiates an allergic foreign body response.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] In the case of an allergic foreign body response, the implant would have to be removed.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] The many examples of implant failure include rupture of silicone breast implants, hip replacement joints, and artificial heart valves, such as the Bjork–Shiley valve, all of which have caused FDA intervention.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] The consequences of implant failure depend on the nature of the implant and its position in the body.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Thus, heart valve failure is likely to threaten the life of the individual, while breast implant or hip joint failure is less likely to be life-threatening.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] Devices implanted directly in the grey matter of the brain produce the highest quality signals, but are prone to scar-tissue build-up, causing the signal to become weaker, or even non-existent, as the body reacts to a foreign object in the brain.
[src:biomaterials/implant-medicine] In 2018, *Implant files*, an investigation made by ICIJ revealed that medical devices that are unsafe and have not been adequately tested were implanted in patients' bodies.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] Titanium was first introduced into surgeries in the 1950s after having been used in dentistry for a decade prior.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] It is now the metal of choice for prosthetics, internal fixation, inner body devices, and instrumentation.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] Titanium is used from head to toe in biomedical implants.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] One can find titanium in neurosurgery, bone conduction hearing aids, false eye implants, spinal fusion cages, pacemakers, toe implants, and shoulder/elbow/hip/knee replacements along with many more.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] The main reason why titanium is often used in the body is due to titanium's biocompatibility and, with surface modifications, bioactive surface.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] The surface characteristics that affect biocompatibility are surface texture, steric hindrance, binding sites, and hydrophobicity (wetting).
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] These characteristics are optimized to create an ideal cellular response.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] Importantly, patient condition can influence the type of modification necessary, for instance in patients with steatotic liver diseases other titanium surface modifications provide better outcomes as compared to patients without fatty liver disease.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] Some medical implants, as well as parts of surgical instruments are coated with titanium nitride (TiN).
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] Titanium is considered the most biocompatible metal due to its resistance to corrosion from bodily fluids, bio-inertness, capacity for osseointegration, and high fatigue limit.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] Titanium's ability to withstand the harsh bodily environment is a result of the protective oxide film that forms naturally in the presence of oxygen.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] The oxide film is strongly adhered, insoluble, and chemically impermeable, preventing unfavorable reactions between the metal and the surrounding environment.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] It has been suggested that titanium's capacity for osseointegration stems from the high dielectric constant of its surface oxide, which does not denature proteins (like tantalum, and cobalt alloys).
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] Its ability to physically bond with bone gives titanium an advantage over other materials that require the use of an adhesive to remain attached.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] Titanium implants last longer and much higher forces are required to break the bonds that join them to the body compared to their alternatives.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] The surface properties of a biomaterial play an important role in determining cellular response (cell adhesion and proliferation) to the material.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] Titanium's microstructure and high surface energy enable it to induce angiogenesis, which assists in the process of osseointegration.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] Titanium can have many different standard electrode potentials depending on its oxidation state.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] Solid titanium has a standard electrode potential of −1.63 V.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] Materials with a greater standard electrode potential are more easily reduced, making them better oxidizing agents.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] As can be seen in the table below, solid titanium prefers to undergo oxidation, making it a better reducing agent.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] Titanium naturally passivates, forming an oxide film that becomes heterogeneous and polarized as a function of exposure time to bodily environments.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] This leads to the increased adsorption of hydroxyl groups, lipoproteins, and glycolipids over time.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] The adsorption of these compounds changes how the material interacts with the body and can improve biocompatibility.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] In titanium alloys such as Ti-Zr and Ti-Nb, zirconium and niobium ions that are liberated due to corrosion are not released into the patient's body, but rather added to the passivation layer.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] The alloying elements in the passive layer add a degree of biocompatibility and corrosion resistance depending on the original alloy composition of the bulk metal prior to corrosion.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] where *Q*ADS is the surface charge density in C⋅cm−2, *M* is the molar mass of the protein in g⋅mol−1, *n* is the number of electrons transferred (in this case, one electron for each protonated amino group in the protein), and *F* is the Faraday constant in C⋅mol−1.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] Wetting occurs as a function of two parameters: surface roughness and surface fraction.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] By increasing wetting, implants can decrease the time required for osseointegration by allowing cells to more readily bind to the surface of an implant.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] Wetting of titanium can be modified by optimizing process parameters such as temperature, time, and pressure (shown in table below).
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] Titanium with stable oxide layers predominantly consisting of TiO2 result in improved wetting of the implant in contact with physiological fluid.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] Mechanical abrasion of the titanium oxide film leads to an increased rate of corrosion.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] Titanium and its alloys are not immune to corrosion when in the human body.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] Titanium alloys are susceptible to hydrogen absorption which can induce precipitation of hydrides and cause embrittlement, leading to material failure.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] The cells at the implant interface are highly sensitive to foreign objects.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] When implants are installed into the body, the cells initiate an inflammatory response which could lead to encapsulation, impairing the functioning of the implanted device.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] The ideal cell response to a bioactive surface is characterized by biomaterial stabilization and integration, as well as the reduction of potential bacterial infection sites on the surface.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] One example of biomaterial integration is a titanium implant with an engineered biointerface covered with biomimetic motifs.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] Surfaces with these biomimetic motifs have shown to enhance integrin binding and signaling and stem cell differentiation.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] Increasing the density of ligand clustering also increased integrin binding.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] A coating consisting of trimers and pentamers increased the bone-implant contact area by 75% when compared to the current clinical standard of uncoated titanium.
[src:biomaterials/titanium-biocompatibility] This increase in area allows for increased cellular integration, and reduces rejection of implanted device.
